d":"Dorset, England","Woolverstone, Suffolk, England":"Woolverstone, Suffolk, England"},"nl":{"1386–1410":"1386–1410","1384–1411":"1384–1411","1385–1460":"1385–1460","1505–1540":"1505–1540","1390–1410":"1390–1410","1408–1477":"1408–1477","1408–Male":"1408–Overleden","1355–1443":"1355–1443","1355–1386":"1355–1386","1385":"1385","1384":"1384","1383":"1383","1460":"1460","1390":"1390","1477":"1477","1411":"1411","1410":"1410","1443":"1443","1355":"1355","1386":"1386","1540":"1540","1408":"1408","1505":"1505","Cossington, Somerset, England":"Cossington, Somerset, England","Woolverstone, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Woolverstone, Suffolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Trenton Manor, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Suffolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Dorset, England":"Dorset, England","Woolverstone, Suffolk, England":"Woolverstone, Suffolk, England"},"en":{"1386–1410":"1386–1410","1384–1411":"1384–1411","1385–1460":"1385–1460","1505–1540":"1505–1540","1390–1410":"1390–1410","1408–1477":"1408–1477","1408–Male":"1408–Deceased","1355–1443":"1355–1443","1355–1386":"1355–1386","1385":"1385","1384":"1384","1383":"1383","1460":"1460","1390":"1390","1477":"1477","1411":"1411","1410":"1410","1443":"1443","1355":"1355","1386":"1386","1540":"1540","1408":"1408","1505":"1505","Cossington, Somerset, England":"Cossington, Somerset, England","Woolverstone, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Woolverstone, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","Trenton Manor, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Dorset, England":"Dorset, England","Woolverstone, Suffolk, England":"Woolverstone, Suffolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Latimer","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: occupational name for a Latinist, a clerk who wrote documents in Latin, from Anglo-Norman French <i>latinier</i>, <i>latim(m)ier</i>. Latin was more or less the universal language of official documents in the Middle Ages, displaced only gradually by the vernacular – in England, by Anglo-Norman French at first, and eventually by English."],"variants":[{"name":"Latner","meanings":["English: occupational name for a worker in or maker of latten or brass, from Middle English <i>latoun</i> ‘brass’ (Old French <i>laton</i>). This name may sometimes have been confused with   Latimer  .","Altered form of German   Lattner   or   Lettner  ."]},{"name":"Lattimore","meanings":["English: variant of   Latimer  ."]},{"name":"Latimore","meanings":["English: variant of   Latimer  ."]},{"name":"Lattimer","meanings":["English: variant of   Latimer  ."]},{"name":"Lattner","meanings":["English: variant of   Latimer  .","German: occupational name for a carpenter who prepared or used laths or slats, from Middle High German <i>latte</i> ‘slat, lath’ + <i>-n</i> (plural suffix) + the agent suffix <i>-er</i>."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William Latimer was born in 1386, in Cossington, Somerset, England, his father, Sir Robert Latimer of Dorset, was 31 and his mother, Lady Margaret de Peche, was 31. He had at least 2 sons with Lady Elizabeth Wolverstone. He die